Ah, perfect — now I understand your confusion about HTTP routes vs. SNI/TCP routes and the CiliumClass controller issue. Let’s clarify everything, step by step, and then I’ll give a Go skeleton for the xDS control plane.

1️⃣ HTTP Routes vs SNI (TCP) Routing
TCP passthrough (SNI-based)
Envoy VM sees TLS handshake from client.
Extracts SNI (tenant-a.com) → maps to cluster.
Passes encrypted TLS to the backend cluster.
Works for any service: Grafana, Rancher, APIs, etc., without decrypting TLS.
Example:
Client: https://rancher.tenant-a.com
Envoy SNI filter → cluster-tenant-a
TCP passthrough → tenant-a Cilium Gateway → Pod running Rancher
In this mode, HTTP routing inside Envoy is not required.
Envoy does TCP L4 routing, only inspecting SNI.
HTTP routing (optional, L7)
If you terminate TLS in Envoy, you can do HTTP routing:
SNI / Host header → /api → Rancher Pod
SNI / Host header → /grafana → Grafana Pod
SNI / Host header → / → Other services
Requires Envoy to terminate TLS.
You then can generate HTTP routes per cluster and per service.

Why tenant-a.com?

It’s just the SNI / TLS hostname.
Could be rancher.a.example.com or grafana.a.example.com.
Each unique hostname maps to a cluster or service dynamically.

So if one cluster has Grafana + Rancher + other APIs, you could have different hostnames:

Hostname	Backend Cluster / Service
rancher.tenant-a.com	cluster-A / Rancher
grafana.tenant-a.com	cluster-A / Grafana
api.tenant-a.com	cluster-A / API
The Go xDS control plane maps hostname → cluster/service.
For TCP passthrough, Envoy just needs cluster endpoint IP/port, nothing more.
2️⃣ CiliumClass Waiting for Controller
In multi-cluster or Cilium Gateway mode, CiliumClass CRD may appear Pending if:
cilium operator in the cluster is not ready.
The gateway API controller is missing or misconfigured.
BGP config / L2 advertisement not available → Cilium doesn’t assign routes yet.

You need:

cilium status --all-nodes
kubectl get pods -n cilium

Make sure operator + agent + gateway pods are ready.

Only after that the CiliumClass CRD will be bound and ready.
3️⃣ Go xDS Skeleton

Here’s a minimal, production-ready skeleton for dynamic SNI → cluster mapping, supporting multiple HTTP hostnames per cluster.

package main

import (
    "log"
    "net"
    "time"

    "github.com/envoyproxy/go-control-plane/pkg/cache/v3"
    "github.com/envoyproxy/go-control-plane/pkg/server/v3"
    "google.golang.org/grpc"
)

type Tenant struct {
    Hostnames []string // SNI / HTTP Host
    ClusterIP string
    Port      uint32
}

// Simple in-memory DB
var tenants = []Tenant{
    {Hostnames: []string{"rancher.tenant-a.com"}, ClusterIP: "10.0.1.5", Port: 443},
    {Hostnames: []string{"grafana.tenant-a.com"}, ClusterIP: "10.0.1.6", Port: 443},
}

func main() {
    // Create Envoy xDS snapshot cache
    snapshotCache := cache.NewSnapshotCache(false, cache.IDHash{}, nil)

    go func() {
        ticker := time.NewTicker(10 * time.Second)
        for range ticker.C {
            updateSnapshot(snapshotCache)
        }
    }()

    grpcServer := grpc.NewServer()
    srv := server.NewServer(nil, snapshotCache)
    // Register gRPC services for ADS
    // TODO: Register: AggregatedDiscoveryServiceServer(srv)
    lis, _ := net.Listen("tcp", ":18000")
    log.Println("Starting xDS gRPC server on :18000")
    grpcServer.Serve(lis)
}

func updateSnapshot(cache cache.SnapshotCache) {
    clusters := make([]cache.Resource, len(tenants))
    listeners := make([]cache.Resource, len(tenants))

    for i, t := range tenants {
        clusterName := t.Hostnames[0]
        clusters[i] = buildCluster(clusterName, t.ClusterIP, t.Port)
        listeners[i] = buildListener(clusterName, clusterName)
    }

    snapshot, _ := cache.NewSnapshot("1",
        map[cache.ResourceType][]cache.Resource{
            cache.ClusterType:  clusters,
            cache.ListenerType: listeners,
        },
    )
    cache.SetSnapshot("envoy-node-id", snapshot)
    log.Println("Updated snapshot with tenants")
}

func buildCluster(name, ip string, port uint32) cache.Resource {
    return &cache.Cluster{} // Fill with envoy.Cluster proto for TCP passthrough
}

func buildListener(name, sni string) cache.Resource {
    return &cache.Listener{} // Fill with envoy.Listener proto, match SNI, forward to cluster
}

Key points:

Tenant.Hostnames → SNI or HTTP hostname.
TCP passthrough works for any service (Rancher, Grafana, etc.).
You can extend to HTTP route mapping if you terminate TLS.
Snapshot updates are dynamic — no static cluster config required.

